UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1412
1 A RESOLUTION recognizing and celebrating Hindu holidays and the resilience of
2 the Hindu people.
3 WHEREAS, the Hindu people have a rich cultural and spiritual heritage that
4 emphasizes the importance of close family bonds, expression of gratitude, introspection
5 and renewal of faith, and harmony, unity, and togetherness; and
6 WHEREAS, Hindus celebrate Dashain, also called Vijaya Dashaimi, by honoring
7 the goddess Durga who prevailed over Mahishura, which is considered as a triumph of
8 good over evil; and
9 WHEREAS, on the 10th day of Dashain, Hindu elders place a tika, a mixture of
10 rice, yogurt, and vermillion, on younger Hindus to bless them with hopes for abundance
11 in the future; and
12 WHEREAS, during Dashain, Hindus visit temples and perform rituals to seek
13 blessings, express gratitude, and reflect on their spiritual journey; and
14 WHEREAS, during the festival of Laxmi Pooja, also known as Dipawali or Diwali,
15 Hindus celebrate Lakshmi, the goddess of wealth and prosperity; and
16 WHEREAS, believing that the goddess will only reside in clean and tidy spaces,
17 Hindus thoroughly clean their homes and decorate them with butter lamps and electric
18 lights in hopes of receiving her blessings; and
19 WHEREAS, Hindus will also buy gold and silver, precious gemstones, new utensils
20 of copper, and brass and bronze for good luck, using the items to worship the goddess
21 Lakshmi at night; and
22 WHEREAS, during the festival of Bhaitika, Hindus celebrate and observe the
23 strong bond between siblings, especially between brothers and sisters; and
24 WHEREAS, the celebration of Bhaitika originated with Yama, the God of Death,
25 visiting his sister, Yamuna. During his visit, Yamuna welcomed him with a tika and
26 special prayers. Being so moved by this gesture, Yama blessed all brothers receiving a
27 tika with long life and prosperity; and
